properties.Title: Winter Storm Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: An intense winter storm system will bring very strong winds as well as snow and blowing snow to Iqaluit and Kimmirut. Very strong winds with gusts to 80 km/h will weaken this morning. Snow will continue to accumulate today and Sunday evening giving a total of 10 to 20 cm. Blowing snow with poor visibilities at times is expected again on Monday. ### Rapidly accumulating snow could make travel difficult over some locations. Visibility may be suddenly reduced at times in heavy snow. Winter storm warnings are issued when multiple types of severe winter weather are expected to occur together. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to NUstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #NUStorm.

Area: Iqaluit, Kimmirut

properties.Title: Weather Advisory In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Winter Weather Travel Advisory in effect for tonight. Snow at times heavy will affect portions of northeastern Ontario tonight. An accumulation of 10 to 15 cm is possible by early Monday morning. Over eastern sections of Manitoulin Island, the snow may become mixed with rain briefly overnight. Travel is expected to be difficult tonight and early Monday morning due to accumulating snow and poor visibility. Motorists are urged to exercise caution. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to ONstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #ONStorm.

properties.Title: Special Weather Statement In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Heavy snow, possibly mixed with rain, arrives tonight. A low pressure system will pass just south of Manitoulin Island tonight and give periods of snow and about 10 centimetres by Monday morning. The snow will begin early this evening and become heavy later this evening. Some rain may mix in with the snow overnight. The west end of the island may receive 8 to 10 centimetres however the east end may receive just over 10 centimetres of heavy wet snow by Monday morning. Travel is expected to be difficult tonight and early Monday morning due to rapidly accumulating snowfall. Snowfall warnings are in effect north of the region, in Espanola, and a snowfall warning may be required for Manitoulin Island if 15 or more centimetres is expected tonight. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to ONstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #ONStorm.
